g in dramatic social transformations at all levels, including the persecution of hundreds of thousands of the country’s citizens. Based on normally inaccessible records of confessions, interrogations, trial transcripts, and depositions, Eight Outcasts tells the stories of eight victims of the Maoist dictatorship. It introduces readers to individuals accused of infractions such as corruption, political wrong thinking, homosexuality, illicit sexual activity, foreign ties, or “historical problems” (connections to the former Kuomintang regime) in the period between the revolution and Mao’s death in 1976. Each chapter brings stories of China’s voiceless citizens to light, broadening our knowledge of this important transitional period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mrz 2021) 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aabuse of power.  achina.  achinese history.  acitizens.  acommunism.  acommunist revolution.  aconfessions.  acorruption.  acultural revolution.  adictator.  afree speech.  agovernment control.  agovernment.  ahistory.  ahomosexuality.  ahuman rights.  aillicit sexual activity.  aimprisonment.  ainterrogations.  akuomintang regime.  amao.  amilitary.  apolitcal activism.  apolitical prisoners.  apolitical repression.  apolitical wrong thinking.  apolitics.  aprotest.  arebellion.  areeducation camps.  aresistance.  arevolution.  asocial change.  asuppression.  atrial transcripts.  aviolence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2019z978311066763940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052097424140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520974241423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520974241.jpg  a978-3-11-066763-9  UC Press eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles